From: huston@mksol.dseg.ti.com (william a huston)
Subject: Linux boot from weird (Session-8) SCSI controller??
Date: Fri, 5 Nov 1993 07:11:20 GMT

I want to install Linux on a second SCSI drive attached to a 
SCSI controler provided with a Digidesign Session-8 (a direct to
disk digital audio recording system). 

Does anyone know if this is do-able, or has any relevant info?

Email answers please, thanks in advance.

(This guy's post started me thinking)

:From: drew@ophelia.cs.colorado.edu (Drew Eckhardt)
:Subject: PC SCSI board manufacture technical contacts wanted
:Date: Sun, 31 Oct 1993 01:43:09 GMT
:
:Under Linux, we try to support a wide variety of PC hardware including
:a myriad of SCSI boards including the Allways IN2000, Adaptec 1520, 1540, 
:and 1740 lines, Future Domain TMC950, TMC1850, and TMC18c50 based boards,
:PAS16 SCSI port, Seagate ST01/ST02, Trantor T128, Ultrastor 14F, 24F, 
:and 34F, and Western Digital 7000.
:
:Unfortunately, some of the drivers fail in some installations (ie,
:the Adaptec 154x driver fails on 'C' revision board if the BIOS options 
:to do extended mapping, auto probe for disks at addresses other than
:0 and 1, or to support > 2 hard disks are enabled, Ultrastor boards 
:at port 0x330 are killed by the network autoprobe code, etc), 
:our time to develop new drivers for boards (like the Adaptec 2742) 
:is very high, and some of our drivers barely work even after 
:reverse engineering the BIOS code (like the Allways IN2000 driver
:which suffers from FIFO overflows) since the technical documentation
:we get from companies through the customer support channels is difficult
:to obtain (in one case, the company denied a programmer's manual 
:existed until I talked with an engineer and asked for the publication
:by name) , sometimes non-existient, sometimes of poor quality, and 
:sometimes late in arriving.
:
:So, I'd like email addresses, and/or fax or phone numbers for 
:technical contacts at PC SCSI board manufactures.  Minimally, 
:these contacts should be able to send out technical publications
:(including eratta sheets) to Linux developers on request, via first 
:class mail, fax, or email, although hopefully a few people will
:be willing to answer technical questions.

Email answers please, thanks in advance.
